Scotland’s independent schools continue to be distinguished by academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with further outstanding examination results and is only supported by individual and joint successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the highest level of care for their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as world citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and sought after in schools as electives.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to someone in a language they understand, you reach their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.”
This is an impressive reminder that we can’t just rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s exam results show that languages with the highest existing rates are at the top of the rankings of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages achieved the grade A on the higher examinations.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students in Mandarin scored A on the higher exams, while 72 percent of students who learned German, 69 percent of students who learned French, and 63 percent of students who scored A in the higher exams.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now considered elective subjects as well as STEM subjects (science, engineering, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills, 17 percent of the reasons employers cited for job vacancy problems were related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary when it comes to preparing young people for their future profession.
As more and more open spaces require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen profession, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage in the future through such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give multilingual people an edge over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct an interview, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15 percent).
For this reason, it is important for today’s children that we now invest in language teaching.
Children who speak multiple languages, especially languages from developing countries, will have better chances of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught at all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while other languages will be taught that are considered to be the most important for the UK with a view to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Wherever your child’s interests are, independent schools will always have a range of languages to choose from with appropriately specialised teachers.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary for their success, whatever the future may look like.
At this time in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of fundamental importance for the future of the country, which is why this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should actually be regarded as "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
You have to do it right.
