North Korea Rejects Unilateral Disarmament Without Confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions would deepen its distrust of the United States and the country would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s annual General Assembly that North Korea took “substantial measures of goodwill” last year, for example, stopping nuclear and missile tests, demolishing the nuclear test site and committing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technologies.
“We do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there is no trust in our national security, and under these circumstances, we will not unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri repeated familiar North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, where North Korea would be rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant insofar as it had not previously rejected unilateral denuclearization.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, in which Kim pledged to work toward the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump pledged guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, while the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington opposes demands for a loosening of strict international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘first denuclearization’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal through coercion, and is even opposed to the ‘Declaration of End of War,’” Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can force us to our knees is a brainwashing of people who don’t know anything about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not go into plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. head of state had highlighted earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other party in the denuclearization issue instead of the US, it would not have come to this standstill in the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula.”
Yet the tone of Ris’ speech differed enormously from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the US mainland with North Korea’s missiles after “evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who had threatened last year with North Korea’s “total destruction,” praised Kim at the United Nations for his courage in disarmament efforts, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and the sanctions would have to remain in place until North Korea was denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t have a time frame for it: “Whether it takes two years, three years, or five months – it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday, “The enforcement of the Security Council’s sanctions must in any case continue vigorously until we have achieved complete, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously intensified sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in order to financially drain Pyongyang’s nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was not successful.
In July, on his departure from Pyongyang, he said progress had been made only to be accused by North Korea hours later of making “walk-like demands.”
North Korea vowed this month at a meeting with Moon to demolish a missile base and a nuclear complex if the United States took “appropriate action.”
He said Kim had told him that the intended “corresponding measures” were security guarantees Trump had given in Singapore, as well as steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Learn to Sleep Enough in a Course
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all undergraduate students get more sleep this year. This is a measure against the spreading macho culture of staying awake with caffeine and learning all night long.
One scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unnecessary when it comes to paying attention to themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and is in his opinion the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to bring the course to life after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about this now, in my last year?’
According to her, no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
This year’s course for the first time explained to students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and sporting performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the university’s health services, said the university had opted for the introduction of the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, students see the image of a room in a residential home and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books, receiving information on the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effects of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, and cancer.
Afterwards, they are encouraged to think about their daily routine using a map of the university grounds with interactive symbols.
“We know that it won’t change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know this – just as you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health,” added Professor Czeisler.
The pride of pushing a “night shift” was still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-growing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
To ensure good enough sleep, the "secret weapon" of all students should be against stress, exhaustion and fear, he said, and weight gain could be avoided as sleep deprivation puts the brain into hunger mode so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having completed one of his courses in his first year at Harvard last year.
He said the course had opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step, all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar degree program before starting their studies at the competitive university.
According to the recommendation of Professor Czeisler, students should be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that comes from electronic screens and LED lighting and can get the circadian rhythm out of the way.
