Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is currently launching a startup with the goal of establishing competition with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on the open source platform Solid by Berners-Lee.
With Solid, users can choose where their data is stored and who gets access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee said that the intention behind Inrupt was “world domination”.
“We need to be active now,” he said on the topic of startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses the technology of Solid, so that users can create their own personal online data storage or a POD.
It can include contact lists, to-do lists, a calendar, a music library, and other tools for the private and corporate sector.
Similar to Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify, all content is available in one browser and at the same time.
The special thing about the personal online data storage is that the user can decide for himself who can access which data.
The company describes this concept as personal empowerment and development over data.
According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is that the company uses resources, processes, and related skills to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, some developers hired to work on this project, as well as a community of volunteer programmers, and a security platform acquired by IBM.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee announced that he and his team will not discuss with Facebook and Google whether to make a comprehensive change that will completely reshape their entire business models overnight.
“We don’t ask for your permission.”
In a contribution to Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt has the task of providing commercial energy generation and an ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new, solid-based web.
In 1994, Berners-Lee redesigned the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been instrumental in the debate on net neutrality.
Even with the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee remains the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely confident about this new era of the web,” he added.
