National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
On a property in the Scottish Highlands, new research is being carried out to show how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that the results will provide further insights into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will track dwarf and mosquito bats, as well as the brown longhorn and water bats in Inverewe Garden in West Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at key positions on the property to record the activities of bats throughout the season.
Employees of the NHS and volunteers will also carry out mobile tests with portable detectors.
A sound analysis of all recordings by experts determines the frequency of bat calls and determines which species does what.
A map and a report of the habitat are then created to create a detailed picture of their behavior at the landscape level.
Rob Dewar, conservation adviser for the NTS, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This data will help determine the benefits of habitat management measures, such as creating meadows, and show how to preserve forest areas for bats and other related species.
Stocks of bats in Scotland and the whole of the United Kingdom have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping places and leads to loss of living space.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and the chemical treatment of building materials or even attacks by domestic cats.
Butterflies are not really blind.
However, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland, takes the issue of bats very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts who regularly carry out investigations, inspections of dormitories and sometimes rescue measures.
The organisation has even set up Scotland’s first and only bat reserve on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s 10 bat species.
Property manager David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for them.
“Here in Threave we have a great area for bats,” he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there’s a lot we don’t yet know about bats, so we’re doing these jobs here and on other goods that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable.”
He stresses the importance of first excluding the presence of bats before maintenance work in the goods, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single nest site could kill up to 400 females and young animals and wipe out the entire population on the spot.
Bats are under protection and it is illegal to kill them, harass them or destroy them or their nesting sites.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
She explains: “We still have a lot to learn about bats and many of our species don’t know what their populations are like.”
