Syria 'ready' to return refugees, foreign minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country devastated by the war that has lasted for over seven years.
In an address to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country is improving.
“Today, thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism, the situation on the ground is more stable and safer,” he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists in order to restore normality.
All conditions have now been set for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian government welcomes assistance in rebuilding the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept conditional aid from countries that had supported the uprising.
