Red Tide Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota Decline
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier districts, more volatile flowering conditions are recorded, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algae bloom extends over about 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of the Hillsborough district, but in fewer places compared to the previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
In the past week, average concentrations in or off the coast of Pinellas County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County have been reported.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier districts.
There have been no new respiratory problems reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
